      "The reason photos often come out rotated incorrectly is related to EXIF orientation data. When you take a photo with a smartphone, the camera sensor always captures the image in landscape orientation (the physical orientation of the sensor). The phone knows you were holding it in portrait mode because its accelerometer detects orientation — so it embeds an EXIF tag that says 'rotate this image 90° when displaying it.' Most photo viewers and websites respect this tag and display the image correctly. But some software, older browsers, and certain platforms strip the EXIF data or ignore the orientation tag, resulting in the image appearing sideways. Rotating the image and re-saving it bakes the rotation into the actual pixel data, which eliminates the dependency on EXIF orientation tags.",
