      "<strong>When to Convert Images to PDF</strong><br/>Scanned documents: If you scan a multi-page document, each page comes out as a separate image file. Converting all pages into a single ordered PDF creates the complete document in a shareable format. Photography portfolios: Rather than sharing a folder of 50 individual JPEGs, a PDF portfolio shows your work in a curated, professionally presented format with one file to download. Client proofs: Designers and photographers share proof sets as PDF so clients see images in the intended sequence and presentation. Form submissions: Many institutions accept scanned forms and ID documents as PDF. Converting your scanned JPEGs to a single PDF makes submission straightforward. Real estate listings: Property photos as a single PDF is standard for many real estate markets. E-commerce product images: A PDF look-book is a common deliverable for wholesale buyers.",
      "<strong>Image Quality in PDF Files</strong><br/>A common concern when converting images to PDF is quality loss. Well-implemented converters embed your images inside the PDF container at their original quality — no re-compression occurs. The resulting PDF file is essentially the sum of all your image files plus a small amount of PDF metadata. If you start with a 2 MB JPEG and convert it to PDF, you get approximately a 2 MB PDF containing that image. Some PDF creation tools automatically compress images during conversion to reduce file size — this is configurable in most professional tools. For a browser-based image-to-PDF converter that prioritizes quality, images are embedded at original quality and no additional compression is applied.",
      "<strong>Page Size and Orientation Settings</strong><br/>When converting images to PDF, you need to decide how the image relates to the page. The main options are: Fit to page — the image is scaled to fit within the page margins while maintaining aspect ratio. This is the most common setting for document-style PDFs. Fill page — the image is scaled to fill the entire page, cropping if necessary. Good for photo portfolios where you want full-bleed images. One image per page — each image gets its own page. Standard for scanned documents and photo proofs. Multiple images per page — useful for contact sheets or thumbnail catalogs. Page size matters when printing: A4 is standard in most of the world, US Letter (8.5×11 inches) in North America. For digital-only PDFs, the page size is less critical.",
      "<strong>Ordering and Organizing Your Images Before Conversion</strong><br/>The order of images in your PDF is determined by the order you add them to the converter. For scanned documents, this means adding pages 1, 2, 3... in sequence. For photo portfolios, think carefully about the narrative flow — leading with your strongest image, building through the middle, and ending with a memorable final image creates a much more compelling presentation than a random order. Most browser-based converters allow you to drag-and-drop reorder images before converting, which is essential for getting the sequence right.",
      "<strong>File Size of the Resulting PDF</strong><br/>A multi-page PDF of high-resolution photos can become very large — if you convert 50 photos at 3 MB each, you get approximately a 150 MB PDF. This can be too large to email (typical limits are 25 MB) or slow to download. Solutions include: compressing the images before converting (using an image compressor to bring each image down to 200–500 KB before adding to PDF), choosing a lower output quality setting in the PDF creator if it offers one, or splitting the PDF into multiple smaller volumes. For most use cases — 5–20 photos at reasonable web quality — the resulting PDF will be under 25 MB and suitable for email attachment.",
