      "<strong>What Exactly Is in Your Photo's Metadata?</strong><br/>The EXIF standard was created in 1995 and has been updated several times since. A typical smartphone photo today might contain 50–100 metadata fields. The most privacy-sensitive are: GPS Latitude and Longitude — your precise location when the photo was taken. GPS Altitude — how high above sea level you were. GPS TimeStamp — the exact UTC time of the photo. Make and Model — your device manufacturer and model (e.g., 'Apple iPhone 15 Pro'). Software — the camera app or editing software version. DateTime Original — the exact date and time the photo was taken. Body Serial Number — your camera or phone's serial number. Less sensitive but potentially revealing: Orientation (which direction you were pointing the camera), Flash (whether flash fired), FocalLength, ApertureValue, ISO, ExposureTime, and MeteringMode.",
